    slug: "huqooq-al-aulad-haqooq-series",
    description: `Huqooq Al Aulad (The Rights of Children), part of the Haqooq Series, is a comprehensive Urdu-language Islamic book that addresses the rights and responsibilities that Islam establishes between parents and their children. Written within a broader scholarly series devoted to Islamic rights and obligations (huqooq), this volume focuses specifically on the often-overlooked topic of what children are entitled to receive from their parents — a subject of immense importance in Islamic jurisprudence and family ethics. The book draws upon the primary sources of Islamic law, including the Quran, the authentic hadith of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), and the established rulings of the classical jurists, to present a thorough and well-referenced treatment of children's rights in Islam. The opening chapters establish the foundational principle that children are a trust (amanah) from Allah, given to parents as a sacred responsibility rather than a personal possession, and that parents will be held accountable before Allah for how they fulfil this trust. The book then proceeds to enumerate the specific rights of children, beginning with the right to life and protection from harm, the right to a good name chosen in accordance with Islamic guidelines, the right to be nurtured and cared for physically, emotionally, and spiritually during the period of dependency, and the right to receive an Islamic education that includes both religious knowledge and practical life skills. The discussion of the right to equitable treatment among siblings is particularly detailed, citing the hadith of Prophet Muhammad in which he admonished a man who favoured one son over another, explaining that fairness among children is a binding obligation upon parents. The section on financial rights covers the duty of parents to provide for their children's material needs including food, clothing, shelter, and medical care, as well as the provisions of inheritance that Islam guarantees to children. The book also addresses the rights of children in special circumstances, including those born out of wedlock, adopted children, and orphans, explaining the Islamic rulings that protect the dignity and welfare of these vulnerable members of society. The later chapters discuss the gradual development of children's rights as they grow, from infancy through childhood to adulthood, and the corresponding changes in parental responsibilities at each stage. Written in clear and scholarly Urdu, this book is an essential reference for parents, scholars, and anyone interested in understanding the comprehensive framework that Islam provides for the protection and nurturing of children.`,
