    slug: "jaanshini-ka-haq-new",
    description: `Jaanshini Ka Haq (The Right of the Heiress) is an important Urdu-language Islamic book that addresses the rights of women in inheritance according to Islamic law, providing a detailed and scholarly examination of a topic that is frequently misunderstood both within Muslim communities and in the broader public discourse. The title refers specifically to the right of a woman — the jaanshini or female heir — to receive her rightful share of inheritance as prescribed by the Quran and the Sunnah, a right that was revolutionary when it was first established in the seventh century and that remains one of the most significant protections that Islam provides for women's financial security and independence. The book begins with a thorough discussion of the pre-Islamic situation regarding women and inheritance, describing how women in many pre-Islamic societies were treated as property to be inherited rather than as heirs entitled to receive inheritance, and how Islam fundamentally transformed this situation by granting women explicit, legally enforceable rights to inherit from their parents, husbands, children, and other relatives. The core chapters provide a verse-by-verse analysis of the four primary Quranic verses that establish the rules of inheritance (known collectively as the ayat al-mawarith), explaining each ruling with reference to the classical commentaries of Ibn Kathir, at-Tabari, al-Qurtubi, and other eminent exegetes. The book covers all categories of female heirs — daughters, wives, mothers, grandmothers, sisters, and aunts — and explains the specific share that each is entitled to receive under different circumstances, including the rules that apply when certain categories of heirs are present or absent. The section on the wisdom and justice underlying the Islamic inheritance system addresses the common criticism that women receive "half the share of men," explaining that this comparison is misleading because it isolates a single ruling from the broader system in which women's financial obligations and entitlements are different from men's, and that in many cases women actually receive larger shares than men. The book also discusses the Islamic prohibition of depriving women of their inheritance, the severity of this sin as established by the Quran and hadith, and the practical measures that Islam provides to ensure that women's inheritance rights are actually fulfilled. Written in clear, scholarly Urdu with extensive references to the primary sources of Islamic law, this book is a valuable resource for scholars, students of Islamic jurisprudence, and any Muslim who wishes to understand the comprehensive and just system of inheritance that Islam has established.`,
    metaDescription: "Jaanshini Ka Haq is a scholarly Urdu book on women's inheritance rights in Islam, explaining Quranic rulings with reference to classical jurisprudence."
