    slug: "jadoo-ki-haqeeqat",
    description: `Jadoo Ki Haqeeqat (The Reality of Magic) is a detailed Urdu-language book that examines the phenomenon of magic (sihr) from a thoroughly Islamic perspective, separating what Islam confirms as real and possible from the superstitions, myths, and fabricated beliefs that have accumulated around this topic over the centuries. The book addresses magic as a subject that has fascinated and frightened human beings throughout history, and that Islam treats with a balanced approach — affirming its existence as a genuine phenomenon while strictly prohibiting its practice and providing comprehensive guidance on protection from its harmful effects. The opening chapters establish the Islamic epistemological framework for understanding magic, explaining that Islam acknowledges the existence of magic as one of the trials and tribulations with which Allah tests humanity, as confirmed by several verses of the Quran, most notably the incident of the two angels Harut and Marut mentioned in Surah al-Baqarah, and by numerous authentic hadith narrations from Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him). The book carefully distinguishes between the Islamic position and the positions of other cultures and belief systems, showing how Islam rejects the attribution of independent power to magic or to those who practice it, affirming instead that all power belongs solely to Allah and that magic can only produce its effects by Allah's permission and within the limits that He has set. The section on the types of magic as described in the Islamic sources covers the various categories that the classical scholars identified, including the magic of illusion and sleight of hand, the magic that affects the mind and emotions, the magic that causes physical illness or harm, and the magic that creates discord between husband and wife (a specific type mentioned in the Quran). The book provides a thorough discussion of the Islamic ruling on magic, establishing that the practice of magic is one of the major sins (kaba'ir) and, according to the majority of scholars, constitutes an act of disbelief (kufr) because it involves seeking the assistance of devils and worshipping other than Allah. The final chapters address the Islamic methods of protection from magic, including the recitation of the Quran (particularly Surah al-Fatiha, Ayat al-Kursi, and the last two surahs), the morning and evening adhkar, the ruqyah (spiritual healing) as practised by the Prophet, and the importance of strong faith and trust in Allah as the ultimate protection against all forms of harm. Written in a scholarly yet accessible Urdu style, this book provides a much-needed corrective to both the excessive fear of magic and the dismissive denial of its reality.`,
    metaDescription: "Jadoo Ki Haqeeqat is a scholarly Urdu book examining the Islamic perspective on magic, its reality, types, prohibition, and methods of protection."
