    slug: "jadoo-tony-ka-ilaaj",
    description: `Jadoo Tony ka Ilaaj (The Treatment of Magic and Spells) is a practical Urdu-language guide that addresses the diagnosis and treatment of magic (sihr), witchcraft, spells, and related spiritual afflictions using the authentic methods prescribed by Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) and the early generations of Muslim scholars. While magic is acknowledged in Islam as a genuine phenomenon that can cause real harm to its victims, the Islamic approach to treating its effects is firmly rooted in the spiritual remedies of the Quran and the Sunnah, completely rejecting the superstitious, harmful, and often un-Islamic methods that are commonly associated with the treatment of magic in popular culture. The book begins with a clear explanation of the Islamic principles that govern the treatment of magic, establishing that ruqyah (spiritual healing through the recitation of the Quran and Prophetic supplications) is the primary and most effective method of treatment, and that any approach that involves shirk (associating partners with Allah), dealing with sorcerers, or using talismans with unknown content is strictly prohibited. The chapters on recognising the symptoms of magic provide a practical guide to the signs that may indicate a person has been affected by magic, including sudden and unexplained changes in behaviour, persistent illness that does not respond to medical treatment, recurring nightmares, unusual aversion to a spouse, and a general sense of unease or oppression — while also cautioning the reader that many of these symptoms can have natural causes and should not be automatically attributed to magic without proper consideration. The core treatment chapters present the detailed methods of Prophetic ruqyah as recorded in the authentic hadith, including the specific Quranic verses and surahs that the Prophet used for healing (Surah al-Fatiha, Ayat al-Kursi, the last two surahs of the Quran, and the first few verses of Surah al-Baqarah), the specific du'as that the Prophet taught for seeking protection and healing, and the method of blowing (nafkh) into water and oil for the affected person to drink and apply. The book also discusses the important topic of preventive measures, including the regular recitation of the morning and evening adhkar, the maintenance of strong faith and trust in Allah, the avoidance of sins and sinful environments, and the cultivation of a close relationship with the Quran through regular recitation and reflection. Written in clear, practical Urdu with references to the authentic sources, this book is an essential resource for those dealing with the effects of magic and for anyone who wishes to protect themselves and their families from spiritual harm.`,
