    slug: "jadu-aur-aasyb-ka-kamyab-elaj",
    description: `Jadu Aur Aasyb Ka Kamyab Elaj (Successful Treatment of Magic and the Evil Eye) is a comprehensive Urdu-language reference work that provides detailed guidance on the Islamic understanding of and remedy for two closely related spiritual afflictions — magic (sihr) and the evil eye (ayn) — using only the methods that are authentically established in the Quran, the Sunnah of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), and the practice of the righteous predecessors. The book brings together the scholarly discussions of both topics in a single volume, recognising that magic and the evil eye often share similar symptoms and can overlap in their effects, and that the Islamic remedies for both are largely the same. The first section of the book is devoted to magic (jadu), beginning with a thorough discussion of its reality as confirmed by the Quran and hadith, the various types of magic that the scholars have identified, and the signs and symptoms that may indicate a person has been afflicted. The treatment section for magic provides step-by-step guidance on performing ruqyah ash-shar'iyyah (the legitimate spiritual healing), including the specific verses to recite, the Prophetic du'as to use, the method of preparing ruqyah water and oil, and the recommended daily routine for someone undergoing treatment. The second section addresses the evil eye (aasyb or nazar), which Islam confirms as a genuine phenomenon that can cause physical illness, financial loss, psychological disturbance, and other forms of harm. The book cites the hadith narrations in which the Prophet explicitly acknowledged the reality of the evil eye and prescribed specific measures for protection and treatment. The discussion covers the difference between the evil eye caused by envy (hasad) and the evil eye caused by admiration without envy, the signs that a person may be affected, and the specific Prophetic remedies including the recitation of Al-Mu'awwidhatayn (the last two surahs), the use of water from the ablution of the person who cast the evil eye (where identifiable), and the general du'as for protection from the evil eye. The book places strong emphasis on the importance of using only those methods that are authentically reported from the Prophet and his companions, warning against the many un-Islamic and potentially harmful practices that are commonly associated with the treatment of magic and the evil eye in some cultures. The final chapters provide a comprehensive daily protection plan that includes the morning and evening adhkar, the recitation of Surah al-Mulk and Surah al-Waqi'ah, and other spiritual practices that serve as a shield against all forms of spiritual harm.`,
