    slug: "maeeshat-o-tijarat-ka-islami-ahkam",
    description: `Maeeshat-o-Tijarat Ka Islami Ahkam (Islamic Rulings on Livelihood and Trade) is a comprehensive Urdu-language reference work on Islamic commercial law and business ethics that provides detailed guidance on the Islamic principles and rulings governing all aspects of earning a living, conducting business, and managing financial affairs. In an era where commercial activity is increasingly complex and where Muslims regularly encounter situations that require knowledge of the Islamic position on financial matters, this book serves as a practical and scholarly guide that addresses a wide range of contemporary business and trade scenarios from the perspective of Islamic law (fiqh al-mu'amalat). The book is organised into major sections that cover the foundational principles of Islamic commercial law, the specific rulings on different types of business transactions, and the ethical framework within which all commercial activity must be conducted. The opening section establishes the Islamic view of wealth and livelihood (ma'eeshat), explaining that earning a halal (permissible) living is not only permitted but is in fact a religious obligation, as the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) taught that seeking halal provision is a form of worship. The discussion covers the conditions that make earnings halal or haram, the types of occupations that are permitted and prohibited in Islam, and the general principles that govern all financial transactions, including mutual consent, transparency, the absence of fraud and deception, and the presence of genuine value in the goods or services being exchanged. The section on trade (tijarat) provides detailed rulings on various types of commercial transactions, including the sale of goods, partnerships, agency arrangements, mortgages, guarantorship, and leasing. The book pays particular attention to the riba (usury/interest)-free nature of Islamic finance, explaining what constitutes riba, the severity of its prohibition as established by the Quran and hadith, and the practical alternatives that Islamic finance offers for common financial needs including lending, borrowing, investment, and insurance. Modern business practices such as e-commerce, franchising, futures trading, insurance, and credit cards are addressed with scholarly analysis that applies the established principles of Islamic jurisprudence to these contemporary situations. The section on business ethics discusses the Islamic standards of fair dealing, honest advertising, fulfilment of contracts, workers' rights, and environmental responsibility. Written in scholarly yet practical Urdu with extensive references to the Quran, hadith, and classical fiqh texts, this book is an essential reference for Muslim business owners, entrepreneurs, and anyone who wishes to ensure that their financial dealings comply with Islamic law.`,
    metaDescription: "Maeeshat-o-Tijarat Ka Islami Ahkam is a comprehensive Urdu reference on Islamic commercial law, business ethics, and halal earning principles."
