    slug: "mera-jeena-mera-marna",
    description: `Mera Jeena Mera Marna (My Living and My Dying) is a deeply reflective Urdu-language book that addresses the two most fundamental realities of human existence — life and death — through the lens of Islamic theology, philosophy, and spirituality. The title, which translates literally to "my living and my dying," echoes the profound Quranic declaration of Prophet Ibrahim (peace be upon him): "My Lord, make me an establisher of prayer, and from my descendants. Our Lord, accept my supplication. Our Lord, forgive me and my parents and the believers on the Day the account is established," and the verse in which the believers are described as those who say, "Our Lord, let not our hearts deviate after You have guided us and grant us from Yourself mercy. Indeed, You are the Bestower." The book explores the Islamic understanding of life as a temporary sojourn — a journey that begins with birth and ends with death, during which each person is tested with responsibilities, trials, and choices that will determine their eternal fate. The section on life (jeena) covers the Islamic perspective on the purpose of human existence, explaining that life is a trust (amanah) from Allah and that every moment of it is an opportunity to earn reward and draw closer to the Creator. The book discusses the Islamic view of success and happiness, contrasting it with the materialistic definitions that dominate modern society, and showing how Islam establishes a framework of meaning and purpose that transcends the temporary pleasures and possessions of this world. The chapters on the stages of life — childhood, youth, adulthood, and old age — provide guidance on how to live each stage in accordance with Islamic teachings, with special attention to the responsibilities and opportunities that are unique to each period. The section on death (marna) addresses the reality that all human beings will face, discussing what Islam teaches about the process of dying, the experience of the soul at the moment of death, and the events that unfold in the grave. The book draws upon the extensive hadith literature on death and the afterlife to provide a vivid and sobering description of what awaits each person after they leave this world, including the questioning by the angels, the experience of the grave, and the journey towards the Day of Judgment. The final chapters provide practical guidance on how to prepare for death while still alive, including the importance of repentance, good deeds, charity, and maintaining a constant awareness of mortality. Written in a reflective and spiritually uplifting Urdu style, this book is a powerful reminder of the transient nature of worldly life and the permanent importance of preparing for the Hereafter.`,
    metaDescription: "Mera Jeena Mera Marna is a reflective Urdu book exploring life and death through Islamic theology, offering spiritual guidance for every stage of existence."
